<p>A Data Scientist who will support our product, sales, leadership and marketing teams with insights gained from analyzing company data. The ideal candidate is adept at using large data sets to find opportunities for product and process optimization and using models to test the effectiveness of different courses of action. They must have strong experience using a variety of data mining/data analysis methods, using a variety of data tools, building and implementing models, using/creating algorithms and creating/running simulations. They must have a proven ability to drive business results with their data-based insights. They must be comfortable working with a wide range of stakeholders and functional teams. The right candidate will have a passion for discovering solutions hidden in large data sets and working with stakeholders to improve business outcomes.</p>

<p><strong>Responsibilities</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Work with stakeholders throughout the organization to identify opportunities for leveraging company data to drive business solutions.</li>
<li>Mine and analyse data from company databases to drive optimization and improvement of product development, marketing techniques and business strategies.</li>
<li>Assess the effectiveness and accuracy of new data sources and data gathering techniques.</li>
<li>Develop custom data models and algorithms to apply to data sets.</li>
<li>Use predictive modelling to increase and optimize customer experiences, revenue generation, ad targeting and other business outcomes.</li>
<li>Develop company A/B testing framework and test model quality.</li>

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. Boutique Outsource Solutions Pty Ltd. – Philippine Branch (BOS) was established in 2014 in response to a need to provide a more personalized approach to the provision of outsource staff. It was set up by its parent company in Australia to specialize in servicing Australian-based finance-related companies who want to set up off-shore operations in the Philippines.

The extensive experience of BOS executive management team and support professionals in the fields of mortgage, process management and business process outsourcing is our edge against the other players in the industry as we are able to deliver a truly exceptional level of service that is made more unique because of our ability to tailor our solutions to our clients’ needs.

And because we offer flexible solutions, our business model is equally effective across a variety of businesses. We give our clients the liberty and the ability to focus on improving their business processes while BOS works to ensure we provide them with all the rest of their operational requirements.

Our Vision

Our vision is to attain sustainable and profitable growth by providing the best quality boutique solutions and services to our clients achieved through our people’s diverse talents and skills in an environment that fosters passion, excellence, honesty and lasting relationships while keeping in mind that work should always be fun and empowering.

In addition, it was made the authorized distributor of the following brands:

• Pioneer Balloons from the U.S.A. in 1995
• BIC Stationery products from France in 2001; BIC Lighters and Shavers (exclusive distributorship)
• Everts Balloons from Malaysia in 2003
• Martha Stewart Crafts

• Disney Art Attack in 2012 (Licensee)
• Crayola (Licensee)

The company was the first to introduce the scrapbooking hobby in the Philippines, creating the brand Craft Easy, formerly known as All About Scrapbooking.

Other of its locally-created brands include:

• Celebration Balloons
• Wrapsody - a line of high-end quality gift wrap paper with special effects
• Wrap 'Em Up – ribbons and quick gift wrapping ideas
• Photofun photo albums

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. In addition, it was made the authorized distributor of the following brands:

• Pioneer Balloons from the U.S.A. in 1995
• BIC Stationery products from France in 2001; BIC Lighters and Shavers (exclusive distributorship)
• Everts Balloons from Malaysia in 2003

• Crayola (Licensee)

The company was the first to introduce the scrapbooking hobby in the Philippines, creating the brand Craft Easy, formerly known as All About Scrapbooking.

Other of its locally-created brands include:

• Celebration Balloons
• Wrapsody - a line of high-end quality gift wrap paper with special effects
• Wrap 'Em Up – ribbons and quick gift wrapping ideas
• Photofun photo albums

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. <p><strong>Main Duties and Responsibilities</strong></p>

<p><strong>I. Organization Diagnoses and Intervention</strong></p>

<li>Drafts questionnaires and/or data gathering guides to facilitate the sessions.</li>
<li>Assists in the actual conduct of data gathering, from the administration of questionnaires to facilitation of sessions.</li>
<li>Assists in designing various processes including organizational charts and process flow to understand and document the work of the unit.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Comes up with an initial analysis based on data gathered from the unit, its stakeholders, and other relevant sources.</li>
<li>Assists in designing organization development (OD) interventions and evaluation processes to address gaps determined in the organizational diagnosis phase. </li>
<li>Carries out OD interventions and initiatives (i.e. competency development, systems review and improvement, change management, succession planning, process re-engineering, etc.) as assigned by the Organization Capability and Succession Section Head.
<ul>
<li>Assists in monitoring, coordinating, implementing, and evaluating organization development projects, keeping track of the deliverables, timelines, and agreements</li>
<li>(Co)Facilitates individual and group discussions, and workshops towards the achievement of the required process.</li>
<li>Proposes action points and process improvements, based on what is applicable and realistic given the unit’s context.</li>
<li>Assists the Workforce Strategy &amp; Branding (WSB) Section and the Career &amp; Learning Development (CLD) in carrying out needed interventions.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>II. Organization and Job Design</strong></p>

<ul>

<li>Works with the Workforce Strategy and Branding Section in ensuring that all job levels accurately reflect the worth of the jobs, that proper classification and nomenclatures are followed.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>III. Talent Development and Succession</strong></p>

<li>Benchmarks best practices in employee learning and development that cover frameworks, assessment strategies, development of interventions, implementation, and evaluation systems.</li>
<li>Assists in monitoring qualification standards and competencies for different job families and job classification.
<ul>
<li>Assists in identifying and developing talent identification criteria.</li>
<li>Assists in the design (review and update) of talent development and succession systems and interventions.</li>
<li>Assists in the conduct and evaluation of the talent development programs.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Assists in communicating and marketing the University’s talent development and succession program to unit heads and employees.

</ul>
</li>
<li>Conducts data gathering and consultations with key stakeholders in the design of learning programs for talents and leaders.
<ul>

</li>
</ul>

<ul>

<li>Keeps abreast of trends and changes happening in the University and with the client.</li>
<li>Manages and maintains relationships with clients.</li>
</ul>

2020-10-06T04:34:19.758750+00:00 2020-12-30T16:00:00+00:00 20000 false quezon-city-local-government Quezon City is a vast and teeming city with a steadily increasing income and occupation of one-third of Metro Manila’s total land area. It now serves as the Philippines’ government center with the legislature and other important government offices located in its area. All of these are reminiscent of the same noble dream that brought forth the creation of the City.

Quezon City is situated on the northeast portion of Metro Manila. It is bounded on the north by Caloocan City and San Jose del Monte City in Bulacan Province, on the east by San Mateo and Marikina, on the south by Pasig and Mandaluyong, San Juan and Manila, and on the west by Valenzuela, Caloocan, and Manila. Its northeastern and eastern boundaries are defined by the Novaliches Watershed and the Marikina River. With an area of 16,112.58 hectares (based on 1995 GIS graphical plot), it is the largest among the sixteen (16) cities and one (1) municipality in the region and is almost one-fourth the size of Metro Manila.

VISION

The Quezon City Government envisions itself to be a model of effective governance and responsible leadership, working in partnership with the citizenry in building a Quality Community.

MISSION

To provide quality service which will make Quezon City an ideal community where people live, work and do business in a hospitable, progressive & peaceful environment.

For more information on the application process, kindly visit the link below to learn more.

<p><strong>What the heck is an Operations Support Manager? </strong></p>

<p>As an Operations Support Manager, you will be supporting the General Manager with the overall business in all administration and operations functions, managing those who provide support to our clients and employees. You will oversee the performance of each team to ensure operations are streamlined and efficient as well as to provide leadership support and growth.</p>

<p><strong>Key Responsibililties:</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Prioritize, delegate &amp; supervise daily operations of the company ensuring a fair distribution of department workload.</li>
<li>Mentor and motivate team members on operations and support issues.</li>
<li>Resolve company day to day issues with clients and team members..</li>
<li>Responsible for maintenance and monthly review of the company’s performance.</li>
<li>Establish workflows, practices and standards to ensure that ample support is provided for operations.</li>
<li>Provide employees direction in analyzing and resolving escalated operational problems.</li>
<li>Track and monitor daily workload to ensure client and operations expectations are met.</li>
<li>Oversee the work of other individuals in each department, providing guidance, supervision, and discipline as needed.</li>
<li>Ability to think quickly and adapt in a flexible work environment.</li>
</ul>

<p>This list is not exhaustive and may be added to or amended at any time, where a reasonable amendment to your responsibilities is required. You will be expected to undertake those duties as required for the successful completion of your job.</p>

<p><strong>What is the Office Culture like? </strong></p>

<p>Each SG Interactive office has its own fun and unique culture, developed by the diverse teams of designers and managers that work there. At the root of each office environment lies the foundational culture that was grown at our headquarters in San Diego.</p>

<p>Here in Manila, a city full of heart, we reflect that description in our office environment. Covering Asia hours and then some, the Asia office culture mirrors the collaborative foundations from our San Diego HQ to bring 24-hour coverage to SG Interactive. This has grown an environment of next level collaboration—a unique mix between independent space, colleagues within and across departments always willing to jump in and lend a hand, and an overall no-fuss can-do attitude. We strongly support each person's personal time, leading us to work hard and work well together so that when you go home, you can really go home. We enjoy all types of music, corny jokes, and a whole flurry of other interests brought about by each new person who joins the team.</p>

<p><strong>Am I going to be able to grow with this company? </strong></p>

<p>We offer a structured and transparent path for each member of the team. You will know where you stand at all times and your manager will highlight exactly what needs to be done in order for you to get to the place you want to be. In addition to offering growth within a given department, we also allow for inter-departmental growth if you show an aptitude in another area. And the growth doesn’t stop there, as the company itself is growing at an amazing rate, providing new and exciting opportunities for our team every day!</p>

<p><strong>Okay, so… What's the catch?</strong></p>

<p>The catch is that you have to bring your ‘A’ game. We expect our employees to bring positive, creative energy into the office everyday. That way we can face any challenge that gets thrown our way, knowing that we will be able to lean on each other for support</p>

<p>The Product Manager (PM) is considered the CEO of the product (Cambium Networks) and is responsible for the strategy, roadmap, and feature definition for that product line. The position also includes marketing, forecasting, and profit &amp; loss responsibilities.</p>

<p>The Product Manager analyzes market and competitive conditions and lays out a product vision that is differentiated and delivers unique value based on customer demands. The PM must spend time in the market to understand their problems and find innovative solutions to the broader market. The role of the product manager spans many activities from strategic to tactical and at its best provides cross-functional leadership—bridging gaps within the company between different functions, most notably between engineering-oriented teams, sales and marketing, and support.</p>

<p>The PM is the person responsible for defining the ‘why’, ‘what,’ and ‘when’ of the product (Cambium Networks) that the global principal will build. The PM is the CEO of the Cambium Networks -- which means they lead cross-functional teams from a product's conception through to its launch. The PM works closely with the global principals to generate more leads, apply strategies and identify prospective partners.</p>

<p>The PM must possess a unique blend of business and technical expertise, a big-picture vision, and the drive to make that vision a reality.</p>

2020-10-06T04:34:35.524284+00:00 2020-12-30T16:00:00+00:00 false quezon-city-local-government Quezon City is a vast and teeming city with a steadily increasing income and occupation of one-third of Metro Manila’s total land area. It now serves as the Philippines’ government center with the legislature and other important government offices located in its area. All of these are reminiscent of the same noble dream that brought forth the creation of the City.

Quezon City is situated on the northeast portion of Metro Manila. It is bounded on the north by Caloocan City and San Jose del Monte City in Bulacan Province, on the east by San Mateo and Marikina, on the south by Pasig and Mandaluyong, San Juan and Manila, and on the west by Valenzuela, Caloocan, and Manila. Its northeastern and eastern boundaries are defined by the Novaliches Watershed and the Marikina River. With an area of 16,112.58 hectares (based on 1995 GIS graphical plot), it is the largest among the sixteen (16) cities and one (1) municipality in the region and is almost one-fourth the size of Metro Manila.

VISION

The Quezon City Government envisions itself to be a model of effective governance and responsible leadership, working in partnership with the citizenry in building a Quality Community.

MISSION

To provide quality service which will make Quezon City an ideal community where people live, work and do business in a hospitable, progressive & peaceful environment.

<ul>
<li>Coordinating efforts for their personal and professional growth in the organization</li>
<li>Creating opportunities for program participants and Staff to understand their growth and change</li>
<li>Equipping them to strengthen and share the same skills with the people they serve (students, co-teachers, etc.); and,</li>
<li>Allowing the Fellows and Staff to reflect on what is happening to them and consider alternative ways of doing things.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>What processes does the job support?</strong> The Training Manager for Human Development works in a highly confidential setting and listens attentively at all times. The HDM is also a non-denominational role and is not about morals or values training nor is the HDM there to dispense advice, but rather help Fellows and Staff to make their own choices. The role requires consultation and direction from the Director of Program and Training.</p>

<p><strong>Why is the job important?</strong> The Training Manager for Human Development listens, analyzes, acts and reviews the Fellows' concerns, and in the process, promotes their leadership development. First, the role provides the space for Fellows to express their feelings, concerns, issues and questions, all in the effort for greater consciousness, understanding and clarity. Second, the HDM analyzes the patterns and trends, and thinks of how best to address and accomplish both leadership and human development. Third, actions are taken, whether as training given, organizational suggestions, or continued conversations. Lastly, a review is done in order to see the effect of the changes instituted.</p>

<p><strong>What position does this job report to?</strong> This role reports to the Director for Programs and Training, with additional coordination with the Chief Programs Officer, and to a certain extent, with the Instructional Coaching Director and Coaches.</p>

<p><strong>What is the span of control of the role?</strong> The Training Manager for Human Development proactively schedules with Fellows either for individual or group colloquia. Aside from the scheduled colloquia, Fellows may have individual colloquia, either through their own scheduling or through the suggestion of their manager. For projects, trainings and programs, this may be given by the executives or directors, or this may be proactively suggested to them.</p>

<p><strong>What are the main challenges facing this role? </strong>This role needs a mature person who has a high level of empathy for all the characters involved, and is able to practice detachment and self-care. The Training Manager for Human Development needs to be able to listen and ask meaningful questions that provoke thoughtful realizations and solutions. The Training Manager for Human Development likewise needs to analyze meta-data in order to give suggestions for the continued leadership and human development of Fellows.</p>		 550 false 2020-11-09T09:40:50.691487+00:00 Public Service and NGOs Paseo de Roxas Makati Philippines Metro Manila 162893 false false Training Manager for Human Development 1 https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/images/TPUJQ3JTCPTD5Q23HKUNFAKQJVRFKPNLQGNCWYDC-5b8dfc5f.jpg 1 <p><u><strong>Knowledge</strong></u></p>
